snippet.textDisplay: Speaking as someone who restricted animal foods for many years and has done a lot of research on evolutionary biology and food: health-wise, the vegan diet is great in the short term, because most people are switching from a Standard American Diet (lots of unhealthy food) to a diet rich in fruits and vegetables. However: long-term, the vegan diet will not give the body everything it needs. This is to be expected, because our ancestors evolved (for over 2 million years) on a diet that contained animal foods, so that's what our body is adapted to; there has been no human population (ever) that ate a vegan diet (but there are human populations that thrive on a primarily animal-foods diet). Consider also that India, which has more vegetarians and vegans than the rest of the world combined, is the diabetes capital of the world. In the long term, we need meat if we want to be fully healthy -- and no amount of concern about animals can change the fact that humans evolved eating meat.

This is to be expected, because our ancestors evolved (for over 2 million years) on a diet that contained animal foods, so that's what our body is adapted to; there has been no human population (ever) that ate a vegan diet (but there are human populations that thrive on a primarily animal-foods diet). Consider also that India, which has more vegetarians and vegans than the rest of the world combined, is the diabetes capital of the world. In the long term, we need meat if we want to be fully healthy -- and no amount of concern about animals can change the fact that humans evolved eating meat.

snippet.textDisplay:
Awesome video per usual! One thing I will say is, please stop referring to veganism as a "health trend". The health trend is going "plant based", which is great!!
But veganism, at it's core, is more a sort of life mantra. It's about living a life of harmony, feeling profound love for all living things, and existing in a way that causes the least harm/impact to earth as possible.

Choosing to live vegan isn't just a diet; it's reducing waste and recycling, composting food scraps, buying more sustainably packaged items or making your own, promoting love through your daily actions/interactions, being helpful, perpetuating positive energy vs negative, etc....

Going vegan isn't some sort of new fad or trend, it's been around for centuries, it's simply choosing caring and kindness above all else.
Love you all 🙏🏼💚✌️

snippet.textDisplay: What micro-nutrients from meat/animal-products are we missing on a plant-based diet according to Max Lugavere!?! We can get everything from plants, because that's where the animals we eat got them in the first place. The problem with animal products is that together with these beneficial nutrients you always get too much trans-fat (which should be zero), saturated fat, cholesterol, animal protein (which raises IGF-1) and heme-iron. Our bodies are more than capable to get everything from plants. Just look at Vitamin A from animal-products vs. beta-carotene. The body is able to regulate the uptake of the latter, but not the vitamin A from animals. That's why it's not safe to get too much while pregnant. The same goes for heme vs. non-heme-iron. It shows that plant sources of vitamin's and minerals were abundant for our species and we evolved to manage their optimum uptake. I'm getting tired of hearing that one diet doesn't fit all, without any evidence.
